{"metadata":{"kernelspec":{"language":"python","display_name":"Python 3","name":"python3"},"language_info":{"name":"python","version":"3.12.12","mimetype":"text/x-python","codemirror_mode":{"name":"ipython","version":3},"pygments_lexer":"ipython3","nbconvert_exporter":"python","file_extension":".py"},"kaggle":{"accelerator":"none","dataSources":[{"sourceType":"datasetVersion","sourceId":15121049,"datasetId":9682486,"databundleVersionId":16008778}],"dockerImageVersionId":31328,"isInternetEnabled":true,"language":"python","sourceType":"notebook","isGpuEnabled":false}},"nbformat_minor":4,"nbformat":4,"cells":[{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"# Credit Card Fraud Detection — Exploratory Data Analysis\n\n## Project Overview\n\nFinancial fraud detection is one of the most important real-world applications of data science and machine learning. In this project, we perform a detailed exploratory data analysis (EDA) on a credit card transaction dataset to understand the structure of the data, identify fraud patterns, and prepare for future predictive modeling.\n\nThis notebook focuses on answering key questions such as:\n\n- How imbalanced is the fraud detection problem?\n- What patterns exist in fraudulent transactions?\n- Do transaction amount, category, gender, location, or time-related features show useful trends?\n- Which variables may be useful for machine learning models?\n\n---\n\n## Objectives\n\nThe main objectives of this notebook are to:\n\n1. Load and combine the training and testing datasets\n2. Inspect the dataset structure and quality\n3. Identify the target variable\n4. Clean unnecessary columns for analysis\n5. Explore fraud distribution\n6. Analyze transaction amount patterns\n7. Investigate fraud across categories and demographics\n8. Examine correlation patterns in numeric features\n9. Generate insights that will guide machine learning in the next project\n\n---\n\n## Why This Problem Matters\n\nFraudulent transactions usually make up a very small fraction of all transactions. This makes fraud detection a highly imbalanced classification problem, where traditional metrics such as accuracy may be misleading.\n\nA strong exploratory analysis helps us understand the problem before building models, and ensures that the machine learning stage is grounded in the actual behavior of the data.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"---\n## Importing Libraries\nWe start by importing the libraries needed for data manipulation, numerical analysis, and visualization.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"import pandas as pd\nimport numpy as np\nimport matplotlib.pyplot as plt\nimport seaborn as sns\n\n# Display settings\npd.set_option(\"display.max_columns\", None)\npd.set_option(\"display.max_colwidth\", 100)\n\n# Plot style\nsns.set(style=\"whitegrid\")\nplt.rcParams[\"figure.figsize\"] = (10, 5)","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2026-03-22T00:18:50.116199Z","iopub.execute_input":"2026-03-22T00:18:50.116645Z","iopub.status.idle":"2026-03-22T00:18:50.126132Z","shell.execute_reply.started":"2026-03-22T00:18:50.116598Z","shell.execute_reply":"2026-03-22T00:18:50.124843Z"}},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"---\n## Loading the Dataset\n\nThis version of the dataset is provided as two separate files:\n\n- `train.csv`\n- `test.csv`\n\nFor exploratory data analysis, we will load both datasets and combine them into a single dataframe so that we can analyze the full transaction distribution.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"TRAIN_PATH = '/kaggle/input/datasets/kaushalnandania/credit-card-fraud-detection/train.csv'\nTEST_PATH = '/kaggle/input/datasets/kaushalnandania/credit-card-fraud-detection/test.csv'\n\ntrain_df = pd.read_csv(TRAIN_PATH)\ntest_df = pd.read_csv(TEST_PATH)\n\nprint(\"Train shape:\", train_df.shape)\nprint(\"Test shape:\", test_df.shape)","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2026-03-22T00:09:09.14369