3Z","iopub.execute_input":"2026-03-22T00:24:26.632279Z","iopub.status.idle":"2026-03-22T00:24:26.654184Z","shell.execute_reply.started":"2026-03-22T00:24:26.632245Z","shell.execute_reply":"2026-03-22T00:24:26.652919Z"}},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"### Insight\n\nThe class distribution shows **1,842,743 legitimate transactions** and **9,651 fraudulent transactions**.\n\nThis means fraudulent transactions are heavily outnumbered by normal transactions, confirming that the dataset is strongly imbalanced. Any future model built on this data must therefore be evaluated carefully, because a naive model could appear accurate while missing most fraud cases.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"plt.figure(figsize=(6, 4))\nsns.barplot(x=fraud_counts.index, y=fraud_counts.values)\nplt.title(\"Fraud vs Non-Fraud Distribution\")\nplt.xlabel(\"Class (0 = Legitimate, 1 = Fraud)\")\nplt.ylabel(\"Number of Transactions\")\nplt.show()","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2026-03-22T00:24:36.553763Z","iopub.execute_input":"2026-03-22T00:24:36.554285Z","iopub.status.idle":"2026-03-22T00:24:36.789527Z","shell.execute_reply.started":"2026-03-22T00:24:36.554254Z","shell.execute_reply":"2026-03-22T00:24:36.788302Z"}},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"---\n## Fraud Percentage\n\nTo better understand the imbalance, we calculate the percentage of fraudulent transactions in the full dataset.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"fraud_percentage = (df[target_col].mean()) * 100\nprint(f\"Fraud percentage: {fraud_percentage:.4f}%\")","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2026-03-22T00:25:13.724263Z","iopub.execute_input":"2026-03-22T00:25:13.724701Z","iopub.status.idle":"2026-03-22T00:25:13.733125Z","shell.execute_reply.started":"2026-03-22T00:25:13.724670Z","shell.execute_reply":"2026-03-22T00:25:13.732215Z"}},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"### Insight\n\nFraud accounts for only **0.5210%** of all transactions.\n\nAlthough this is still a small minority class, it is slightly higher than some other benchmark fraud datasets. Even so, fraud remains rare enough that accuracy alone would be misleading, and the modeling stage should focus more on recall, precision, and F1-score.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"---\n## Transaction Amount Analysis\n\nThe `amt` column represents transaction amount.\n\nWe begin by studying the overall distribution of transaction values to understand:\n- whether most transactions are small or large\n- whether outliers exist\n- whether fraud and non-fraud transactions differ in amount","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"df['amt'].describe()","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2026-03-22T00:26:55.813616Z","iopub.execute_input":"2026-03-22T00:26:55.814075Z","iopub.status.idle":"2026-03-22T00:26:55.894547Z","shell.execute_reply.started":"2026-03-22T00:26:55.814035Z","shell.execute_reply":"2026-03-22T00:26:55.893341Z"}},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"### Insight\n\nThe transaction amount statistics show a highly right-skewed distribution:\n\n- **Mean:** 70.06  \n- **Median:** 47.45  \n- **75th percentile:** 83.10  \n- **Maximum:** 28,948.90\n\nThis tells us that most transactions are relatively small or moderate in value, while a small number of extreme high-value transactions pull the mean upward. The strong gap between the median and the maximum confirms the presence of large outliers.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"---\n## Transaction Amount by Fraud Class\n\nWe now compare transaction amounts between legitimate and fraudulent transactions.\n\nThis helps us see whether fraudulent activity tends to occur at unusually high or low values.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"plt.figure(figsize=(10, 5))\nsns.boxplot(x=target_col, y='amt'